    <p>
      Now that we have visually explored the relationship between <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, <m>\vw_1</m>, and <m>\vw_2</m>, we will see how we can find formulas that allow us to compute <m>\vw_1</m> and <m>\vw_2</m> in terms of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act-dotproduct-proj-formula">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> are vectors in <m>\R^n</m>. We wish to find <m>\vw_1</m> and <m>\vw_2</m> so that <m>\vw_1</m> is parallel to <m>\vv</m> and <m>\vw_2</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vv</m>, as shown in <xref ref="projexamples"/>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why <m>\vu=\vw_1 + \vw_2</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <xref ref="projexamples"/> and the geometric definition of vector addition justify this.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <xref ref="projexamples"/> illustrates these vectors with the tail of <m>\vw_2</m> at the tip of <m>\vw_1</m> and <m>\vu</m> going from the tail of <m>\vw_1</m> to the tip of <m>\vu</m>. This is how we understood vector addition.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\vu\cdot \vv</m> as <m>(\vw_1+\vw_2)\cdot \vv</m>. Simplify your answer as much as possible, using the fact that <m>\vw_2</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vv</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vw_1\cdot \vv</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\vu \cdot \vv= \amp  (\vw_1+\vw_2)\cdot\vv</mrow>
              <mrow>= \amp  (\vw_1)\cdot\vv + (\vw_2)\cdot\vv</mrow>
              <mrow>= \amp  (\vw_1)\cdot\vv </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Since <m>\vw_1</m> is parallel to <m>\vv</m>, there is a scalar <m>k</m> so that <m>\vw_1 = k\vv</m>. Substitute <m>k\vv</m> for <m>\vw_1</m> in your answer to the previous part and then solve for <m>k</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>k=\frac{\vu\cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot \vv}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>k=\frac{\vu\cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot \vv}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give a formula for <m>\vw_1</m> purely in terms of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Your answer should be a scalar multiple of <m>\vv</m> and include two dot products and a fraction.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\vw_1 = \frac{\vu\cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot vv}\vv</m>
          </p>
        </answer>        
        <solution>
          <p>
            Substituting <m>k=\frac{\vu\cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot \vv}</m> into <m>\vw_1 = k\vv</m> yields <m>\vw_1 = \frac{\vu\cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot vv}\vv</m>. 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
    <p>
      The vector <m>\vw_1</m> we have been considering in this subsection is so useful that it has specific notation. We use the previous activity to state the following definition.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-vector-projections">
      <statement>
        <p><idx><h>vector</h><h>component in the direction of</h></idx>
          Let <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> be vectors in <m>\R^n</m>. The <term>projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m></term> is the vector
          <mdn>
            <mrow>\proj_{\vv} \vu \amp = \frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot\vv} \vv</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \left(\frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}\right) \frac{\vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}</mrow>
          </mdn>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p><idx><h>vector</h><h>component in the direction of</h></idx>
      Using the property that the dot prodcut of a vector with itself is the square of the vector's magnitude, we can write <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu = \left(\frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}\right) \frac{\vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}</m>. Since <m>\vv/\vecmag{\vv}</m> is a unit vector, we can see from this form that the magnitude of <m>\proj_{\vv}\vu</m> is <m>(\vu\cdot \vv)/\vecmag{\vv}</m>. We call this scalar the <term>component of <m>\vu</m> in the direction of <m>\vv</m></term> and denote it by
      <me>
        \comp_{\vv} \vu = \frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}
      </me>.
      Recalling from earlier in the section that <m>\vu\cdot \vv = \vecmag{\vu}\vecmag{\vv}\cos(\theta)</m>, where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>, we can also write
      <me>
        \comp_{\vv}\vu = \frac{\vecmag{\vu}\vecmag{\vv}\cos(\theta)}{\vecmag{\vv}} = \vecmag{\vu}\cos(\theta)
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Vector subtraction also gives us a way to solve for the piece <m>\vw_2</m> of <m>\vu</m> that is orthogonal to <m>\vv</m>. We find <m>\vw_2=\vu-\vw_1= \vu-\frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv \cdot \vv} \vv</m>. The <term>orthogonal projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m></term> is 
      <me>
        \proj_{\perp \vv} \vu = \vu - \proj_{\vv} \vu = \vu - \frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot\vv} \vv
      </me>.
      These relationships (for one configuration of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>) are shown in <xref ref="fig-dotproduct-proj-labeled"/>. <em>Remember that the length of <m>\proj_{\vv}\vu</m> is <m>\comp_{\vv}\vu</m>.</em> Also notice how the arrangement of the vectors provides an illustration of the fact that <m>\vu = \proj_{\vv}\vu + \proj_{\perp \vv}{\vu}</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-dotproduct-proj-labeled">
      <caption>The relationship between <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, the projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> and the orthogonal projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m>.</caption>
        <image width="45%" label="img-proj-def-labeled">
          <description><p>Vector <m>\vv</m> points horizontally with <m>\vu</m> above it making an acute angle <m>\theta</m>. The vector <m>\proj_{\perp \vv}\vu</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vv</m>, pointing upward so that the tip of <m>\vw_2</m> coincides with the tip of <m>\vu</m>. Vector <m>\proj_{\vv}</m> has the same tail as <m>\vv</m> and its tip coincides with the tail of <m>\vw_2</m>.</p></description>
          <sageplot>
            var('t')
            plot8=arrow((0,0),(3,0),color="black",width=3,axes=False,aspect_ratio=1)
            plot8+=text("$\\vec{u}$",(1.4,2.4),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot8+=arrow((0,0),(1.6,2.4),color="black",width=3)
            plot8+=text("$\\vec{v}$",(3.1,0),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot8+=arrow((0,0),(1.6,0),color="blue",width=4)
            plot8+=text("$\\mathrm{proj}_{\\vec{v}}\\vec{u}$",(0.75,-0.2),color="blue",fontsize=25)
            plot8+=arrow((1.6,0),(1.6,2.4),color="red",width=4)
            plot8+=text("$\\mathrm{proj}_{\\perp\\vec{v}}\\vec{u}$",(2.1,1.2),color="red",fontsize=25)
            plot8+=text("$\\theta$",(0.4,0.2),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot8
          </sageplot>
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Notice in <xref ref="fig-dotproduct-proj-labeled"/> that you can also see 
      <me>
        \cos(\theta) = \frac{\vecmag{\proj_{\vv}\vu}}{\vecmag{\vu}} = \frac{\comp_{\vv}\vu}{\vecmag{\vu}},
      </me>
      which aligns with our earlier formula <m>\comp_{\vv}\vu = \vecmag{\vu}\cos(\theta)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The component of <m>\vu</m> in the direction of <m>\vv</m> will be a scalar measure of how much of <m>\vu</m> is parallel to <m>\vv</m>. In fact, this shows up in the second formula for <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu</m>. Specifically, we can write <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu = (\comp_{\vv} \vu) \frac{\vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}</m>, which separates the projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> into   how much of <m>\vu</m> is parallel to <m>\vv</m> (a scalar) times the unit vector in the direction of <m>\vv</m>. This useful idea of separating the magnitude of a vector and the direction of a vector (as described by a unit vector) will be used in the analysis of many vector calculations. The first expression for <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu = \frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot\vv} \vv</m> can be interpreted conceptually as saying the projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> must be parallel to <m>\vv</m> and <m>\frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot\vv}</m> is closely related to the length of <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="vecprojex">
      <p>
        In this example we will look at calculating and making sense of the different parts of the projection of <m>\langle 4,3\rangle </m> onto <m>\langle 0,2 \rangle</m>. For notational purposes, we will let <m>\vu = \langle 4,3\rangle </m> and  <m>\vv = \langle 0,2 \rangle</m>. Applying <xref ref="def-vector-projections" />, we find
        <md>
          <mrow> \proj_\vv \vu \amp= \left(\frac{\langle 4,3\rangle \cdot \langle 0,2 \rangle  }{\langle 0,2 \rangle \cdot \langle 0,2 \rangle} \right) \langle 0,2 \rangle </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \left(\frac{6}{4}\right) \langle 0,2 \rangle </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \left(\frac{3}{2}\right) \langle 0,2 \rangle = \langle 0,3 \rangle </mrow>
        </md>.
        Using the other formula for the projection, we have
        <md>
          <mrow> \proj_\vv \vu \amp= \left(\frac{\langle 4,3\rangle \cdot \langle 0,2 \rangle  }{\vecmag{\langle 0,2 \rangle}} \right) \frac{\langle 0,2 \rangle}{\vecmag{\langle 0,2 \rangle }} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= \left(\frac{6}{2}\right) \frac{\langle 0,2 \rangle}{2} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp= (3) \langle 0,1 \rangle = \langle 0,3 \rangle </mrow>
        </md>.
        Note that the scalar <m>(3)</m> in the last equation is <m>\comp_\vv \vu</m> and the vector <m>\langle 0,1\rangle</m> is the unit vector in the direction of <m>\vv</m>. 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="projexplot">
        <caption>A plot of <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, <m>\proj_\vv \va</m>, and <m>\proj_{\perp \vv} \vu</m> </caption>
        <image width="75%" label="img-projexplot">
          <description><p> A plot of <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>, <m>\proj_\vv \vu</m>, and <m>\proj_{\perp \vv} \vu</m></p></description>
          <sageplot>
            plot10=arrow((0,0),(4,3),color="black",width=3,gridlines=True)
            plot10+=arrow((0,0),(0,2),color="black",width=3)
            plot10+=arrow((0,0),(0,3),color="red",width=2)
            plot10+=arrow((0,3),(4,3),color="blue",width=2)
            plot10+=text("$\\vec{u}$",(4.2,3.2),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot10+=text("$\\vec{v}$",(0.1,1.25),color="black",fontsize=25)
            plot10+=text("$\\mathrm{proj}_{\\vec{v}} \\vec{u}$",(0.5,2.25),color="red",fontsize=25)
            plot10+=text("$\\mathrm{proj}_{\\perp \\vec{v}} \\vec{u}$",(2.5,3.25),color="blue",fontsize=25)
            plot10
          </sageplot>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        We can now compute the orthogonal projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> using <m>\proj_\vv \vu</m>.
        <me>
          \proj_{\perp \vv} \vu = \vu - \proj_\vv \vu = \langle 4,3 \rangle - \langle 0,3\rangle =\langle 4,0\rangle
        </me>.
        We can summarize these calculations as follows:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              The projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> is asking how much of <m>\langle 4,3 \rangle</m> is in the vertical direction.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> can be split into the scalar <m>3</m>, the component of <m>\vu</m> in the direction of <m>\vv</m>, and the unit vector in the direction of <m>\vv</m>, <m>\langle 0,1 \rangle </m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The orthogonal projection of <m>\vu</m> onto <m>\vv</m> will be given by how much of <m>\vu</m> is horizontal because we subtract out all of the vertical component of <m>\vu</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul> 
      </p>
      <!-- <p>
        This example allows us to contrast the precise meaning of the projection vector with the the original interpretation of the dot product. Specifically, we used the dot product of <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> to measure how much these vectors move together and found that <m>\langle 4,3\rangle \cdot \langle 0,2 \rangle=6</m>. So <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> move together a <q>positive</q> amount. This measurement is used in the coefficent for both forms of the projection equation. In the first equation, 
        we use the ratio <m>\frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot\vv}</m> to measure how much <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> move together in comparison to the size of <m>\vv</m>. In the second equation for the projection, we use the ratio <m>\frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vecmag{\vv}}</m> to measure how much <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m> move together in comparison to unit vector in the direction of <m>\vv</m>. 
      </p> -->
    </example>
    <p>
      Going forward, we will use the projection more often than the dot product by itself. This is because the projection precisely measures how much of one vector is in a particular direction rather than the much vauger measurement of the type of angle between the vectors.
    </p>
    <p>
      The following activity gives you an opportunity to practice the computations involved with finding parallel and orthogonal projections.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="A_9_3_4">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let <m>\vu = \langle 2, 6 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\vv = \langle 4, -8 \rangle</m>. Find <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu</m>, <m>\comp_{\vv} \vu</m>,  and <m>\proj_{\perp \vv} \vu</m>. Draw a picture to illustrate the vectors involved. Finally, express <m>\vu</m> as the sum of two vectors where one is parallel to <m>\vv</m> and the other is perpendicular to <m>\vv</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
             <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu = \langle -2, 4 \rangle</m>, <m>\comp_{\vv} \vu = \frac{-40}{\sqrt{80}}</m>, <m>\proj_{\perp \vv} \vu = \angle 4, 2 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu = \frac{\vu\cdot\vv}{\vv\cdot\vv}  \vv = \frac{(2)(4) + (6)(-8)}{(4)(4) + (-8)(-8)}  \rangle 4, -8 \rangle = \frac{-40}{80}  \langle 4, -8 \rangle = \langle -2, 4 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\comp_{\vv} \vu = \frac{\vu\cdot\vv}{\vv\cdot\vv} = \frac{(2)(4) + (6)(-8)}{\sqrt{(4)^2 + (-8)^2}} = \frac{-40}{\sqrt{80}}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\vu = \proj_{\vv} \vu + \proj_{\perp \vv} \vu </m>.
          </p>
          
          <p>
            <m>\langle 2, 6 \rangle = \langle -2, 4 \rangle + \langle a, b \rangle</m>. Solve for <m>\proj_{\perp \vv} \vu</m> to get <m>\langle 4, 2 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
          <image width="75%" label="img-projection-activity">
            <sageplot>
              u=vector([2,6])
              v=vector([4,-8])
              putov=(u.dot_product(v)/v.dot_product(v))*v
              perp=u-putov
              plot11=arrow((0,0),u,color="black",width=3,aspect_ratio=1)
              plot11+=arrow((0,0),v,color="black",width=3)
              plot11+=text("$\\vec{u}$",1.05*u,color="black",fontsize=25)
              plot11+=text("$\\vec{v}$",1.05*v,color="black",fontsize=25)
              plot11+=arrow((0,0),putov,color="red",width=2)
              plot11+=arrow(putov,u,color="blue",width=2)
              plot11+=text("$\\mathrm{proj}_{\\vec{v}} \\vec{u}$",0.5*putov-0.5*perp,color="red",fontsize=25)
              plot11+=text("$\\mathrm{proj}_{\\perp \\vec{v}} \\vec{u}$",1.5*putov+0.5*perp,color="blue",fontsize=25)
              plot11
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Now let <m>\vw = \langle -2,4 \rangle </m>. Add <m>\vw</m> to the picture you drew in the previous part. Without doing any calculations, find <m>\proj_{\vw} \vu</m>. Explain your reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\proj_{\vw} \vu = \langle -2, 4 \rangle</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\vw = \langle -2 ,4 \rangle</m> is equal to <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu</m>. If we sketch the <m>\proj_{\vv} \vu = \langle -2, 4 \rangle</m> onto <m>\langle -2, 4 \rangle</m>, these are the same vectors.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find a vector <m>\vw</m> not parallel to <m>\vz = \langle 3,4 \rangle </m> such that <m>\proj_{\vz} \vw</m> has length <m>10</m>. Note that there are infinitely many different answers!
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            There are an infinite number of answers.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <m>\proj_{\vz} \vw = \frac{\vw\cdot\vz}{\vz\cdot\vz}  \vv = \frac{(w_1)(3) + (w_2)(4)}{(3)(3) + (4)(4)}  \langle 3, 4 \rangle = \frac{3w_1 + 4w_2}{25}  \langle 3, 4 \rangle</m>. The vector <m>\langle 6, 8 </m> has a magnitude of 10. So when <m>\frac{3w_1 + 4w_2}{25} = 2</m>, then <m>\proj_{\vz} \vw = 10</m>. Therefore, <m>3w_1 + 4w_2 = 50</m>. One such vector is <m>\vw = \langle 10, 5 \rangle</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
    <p>
      It is important to note that in general <m>\proj_{\vv} \vw \neq \proj_{\vw} \vv</m>. You can explore in <xref ref="ex-projnotsym" /> how switching the vectors in the projection formula will give a different results.
    </p>

  
  </subsection>
<subsection>
    <title>Work, Force, and Displacement</title>
    <p>
      In physics, work is a measure of the energy required to apply a force to an object through a displacement. In <xref ref="workex" />, we can see a diagram showing the force applied to a refrigerator (in orange) that is used to move the refrigerator from point <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>. The change in location, <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>, is called the <term>displacement</term>. Notice that not all of the force is in the direction of the displacement. The work done on the refrigerator only depends on the amount of force that is in the direction of <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="workex">
      <caption>A diagram showing the force applied to the refrigerator as the refrigerator is moved from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> </caption>
      <image width="70%" label="img-workex">
        <description><p> A diagram showing the force applied to the refrigerator as the refrigerator is moved from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>. The momement is rightward and parallel to the ground, but the force is rightward and slightly upward.</p></description>
        <sageplot>
          plot7=polygon([(0,0),(0,1),(1/2,1),(1/2,0),(0,0)],color="orange",axes=False,aspect_ratio=1,xmin=-1/2,xmax=3.5,ymin=-0.25,ymax=1.25)
          plot7+=line([(0,0),(0,1),(1/2,1),(1/2,0),(0,0)],color="black")
          plot7+=arrow((0,0),(3,0),width=4,color="black")+point((0,0),color="black",size=35)+point((3,0),color="black",size=35)
          plot7+=text("$A$",(-0.2,-0.2),color="black",fontsize=25)+text("$B$",(3.2,-0.2),color="black",fontsize=25)
          plot7+=arrow((0,1/2),(1,1),color="blue",width=3)
          plot7+=text("$\\vec{F}$",(1.1,1.1),color="blue",fontsize=25)
          plot7+=line([(0,1/2),(1,1/2)],color="gray",thickness=3)+line([(1,1/2),(1,1)],color="gray",linestyle="--")
          plot7+=text("$\\Vert \\vec{F} \\Vert \\cos(\\theta)$",(1,0.25),color="gray",fontsize=20)
          plot7
        </sageplot>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The work required to move the refrigerator is
      <me>
        W = \vF\cdot\overrightarrow{AB} = \vecmag{\vF} \vecmag{\overrightarrow{AB}} \cos(\theta)
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      This means that the work is determined only by the magnitude of the force applied parallel to the displacement and the length of the displacement. In fact, work is closely related to the projection of the force vector onto the displacement vector. (More precisely, it is the product of the component of the force vector in the direction of the displacement vector times the magnitude of the displacement vector.)
    </p>
    <p>
      The units commonly used for work are Joules or Newton-meters in the metric system and foot-pounds in customary units. (In electrical settings, units such as coulomb-volts or kilowatt-hours may be used.) Note that these units come from work being the dot product of a force vector, using units of Newtons or pounds, and a displacement vector, using units of meters or feet.

    </p>
    <activity xml:id="A_9_3_1">
      <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the work done by a 25 pound force acting at a <m>30^{\circ}</m> angle to the direction of the object's motion, if the object is pulled 10 feet. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>W = 216.506</m> lb-ft.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>W = 25 \cdot 10\cdot \cos(30^{\circ}) = 216.506</m> lb-ft.
        </p>
      </solution>

       <p>

       </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine if more work or less work is done if the angle to the direction of the object's motion is <m>60^\circ</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Less work is done.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            If the angle is increased, the value of <m>\cos(\theta)</m> decreases and approaches 0. Therefore, less work is done if the angle to the direction of the object's motion is <m>60^{\circ}</m>. <m>W = 25\cdot 10\cdot \cos(60^{\circ}) = 125</m> lb-ft.            
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </subsection>

  <outcomes>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The dot product of two vectors in <m>\R^n</m>, <m>\vu = \langle u_1,
            u_2, \ldots, u_n \rangle</m> and <m>\vv = \langle v_1, v_2, \ldots, v_n
            \rangle</m>, is the scalar
          <me>
            \vu \cdot \vv = u_1v_1 + u_2v_2 + \cdots + u_nv_n
          </me>.
          The dot product is related to the length of a vector since
            <m>\vu\cdot\vu = \vecmag{\vu}^2</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The dot product provides us with information about the angle
            between two vectors since
          <me>
            \vu\cdot\vv = \vecmag{\vu} \vecmag{\vv}\cos(\theta),
          </me>
          where <m>\theta</m> is the angle
            between <m>\vu</m> and <m>\vv</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Two vectors are orthogonal if the angle between them
            is <m>\pi/2</m>. In terms of the dot product, the vectors <m>\vu</m> and
            <m>\vv</m> are orthogonal if and only if <m>\vu \cdot \vv = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The projection of a vector <m>\vu</m> in <m>\R^n</m> onto a vector <m>\vv</m>
            in <m>\R^n</m> is the vector
          <me>
            \proj_{\vv} \vu = \frac{\vu \cdot \vv}{\vv\cdot\vv} \vv.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>

  </outcomes>


